---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from 'astrowind:config';

const crumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
  { name: 'R&D Center', href: '/randdcenter' },
  { name: 'Fabric Engineering & Development' },
];

const metadata = {
  title: `Fabric Engineering & Development — Fabric Construction & Weave Design | ${SITE.name}`,
  description: `Explore our Fabric Engineering & Development lab for fabric construction design, weave engineering, coating technology, and custom textile development. Contact our engineering team to start your next fabric project.`,
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata} breadcrumbs={crumbs}>
  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 py-16 sm:py-20 mx-auto max-w-5xl">
    <a href="/randdcenter" class="text-sm text-gray-500 hover:underline">&larr; Back to R&D Center</a>
    <div class="mt-4 grid md:grid-cols-5 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-3">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary uppercase tracking-wider">Lab 02</p>
        <h1 class="mt-2 text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold">Fabric Engineering & Development</h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg text-muted">Fabric construction, weave engineering, coating technology</p>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-2">
        <img
          src="/images/seekingtex/factory/fabric-engineering-CAD.webp"
          alt="Seekingtex fabric engineering CAD design workstation"
          class="w-full h-48 object-cover rounded-xl"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 pb-12 mx-auto max-w-4xl prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert">
    <h2>Where performance meets textile engineering</h2>
    <p>
      The fabric construction is the foundation of every functional textile. It must be engineered to deliver specific
      performance characteristics — tensile strength for durability, stretch for comfort, breathability for moisture
      management, and dimensional stability for long-term reliability. At {SITE.name}, our Fabric Engineering & Development
      lab combines advanced CAD-based fabric design, structural analysis, and decades of textile engineering
      experience to deliver fabrics that are optimized for their intended application — not generic constructions
      adapted from a catalogue.
    </p>
    <p>
      We work with three primary fabric construction types — woven, knitted, and non-woven — and have the engineering
      capability to design, simulate, and validate each one in-house.
    </p>

    <h2>Design tools and standards</h2>
    <p>Our digital engineering environment includes:</p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Capability</th><th>Software / Tool</th><th>Application</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr
          ><td>Fabric construction CAD</td><td>ScotWeave / EAT DesignScope</td><td
            >Weave pattern, knit structure, non-woven web design</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Finite element analysis</td><td>ANSYS Mechanical & LS-DYNA</td><td
            >Stress mapping, tear propagation, stretch recovery simulation</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Computational fluid dynamics</td><td>Ansys Fluent</td><td
            >Air permeability modeling, moisture vapor transport simulation</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Coating & laminate engineering</td><td>CoatingPro / custom models</td><td
            >Layer stack-up design, thickness optimization, weight estimation</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr><td>Weave simulation</td><td>TexGen / WiseTex</td><td>Fabric geometry modeling, crimp analysis, permeability prediction</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Our engineering workflow</h2>
    <p>
      Every fabric construction, whether it is a standard product or a fully custom development, follows a rigorous five-stage
      process:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Concept & requirements gathering</strong> — We meet with you to define performance targets, end-use environment,
        regulatory requirements, and any special finishing needs (UPF, water repellency, antimicrobial).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fabric construction design</strong> — The fabric structure is modeled in CAD software and checked
        for cover factor, crimp ratio, areal density, and mechanical properties using built-in analysis tools.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Structural FEA</strong> — Load cases are defined: tensile (warp/weft), tear (trapezoid/tongue), and
        burst (diaphragm). Stress distribution is reviewed; safety factor minimum 2.5 is mandatory.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Coating & laminate optimization</strong> — The coating or laminate stack is simulated for adhesion,
        flexibility, and barrier performance. Parameters are iteratively optimized.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Design review & release</strong> — The complete engineering package (construction design, FEA report,
        coating specification, weight estimate, finishing recipe) is reviewed by our senior textile engineer before release to sampling.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="not-prose my-10 p-6 rounded-xl bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 mb-3 uppercase tracking-wider">
        FEA Tensile Distribution — Plain Weave Polyester 150D
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="block text-2xl font-bold text-blue-600">2.8 : 1</span>
          <span class="text-gray-500">Safety factor at max load</span>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="block text-2xl font-bold text-blue-600">15.2 %</span>
          <span class="text-gray-500">Stretch recovery vs previous construction</span>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="block text-2xl font-bold text-blue-600">87 N/cm</span>
          <span class="text-gray-500">Peak tensile strength (warp direction)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="block text-2xl font-bold text-blue-600">18 000 h</span>
          <span class="text-gray-500">Cumulative FEA runtime in 2025</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Customization: your fabric, your rules</h2>
    <p>
      No two applications have identical requirements. An outdoor performance fabric needs high UPF and water repellency; a medical textile needs breathability and antimicrobial properties; an industrial fabric needs abrasion resistance and dimensional stability. We do not force your application into a pre-existing fabric construction. We design from your specification upward.
    </p>
    <p>Examples of recent custom fabric engineering projects:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        A high-tenacity polyester woven fabric for outdoor upholstery, with reinforced weft for enhanced tear strength (+15 %
        tear resistance).
      </li>
      <li>
        A lightweight nylon ripstop for performance outerwear, with integrated breathable coating and DWR finish.
      </li>
      <li>
        A stretch-knit polyester/spandex blend for activewear, engineered for 4-way stretch with moisture-wicking and antimicrobial finish.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Our engineers</h2>
    <p>
      The studio is led by a senior textile engineer with 14 years of experience in technical fabric design, supported by
      two mechanical engineers specialized in FEA and textile mechanics. All three hold advanced degrees in textile engineering or
      materials science from internationally recognized universities. The team publishes regularly in industry journals
      and presents at conferences such as the International Conference on Textile Engineering and the AATCC Symposium.
    </p>

    <h2>Partner with us on your next fabric</h2>
    <p>
      From the first concept sketch to the final engineering report, our Fabric Engineering & Development lab is your partner in creating
      a fabric that is not just produced — but engineered. We invest the simulation hours upfront so that every yarn,
      every weave pattern, and every coating layer is there for a reason.
    </p>
    <p>
      Whether you need a minor modification to an existing fabric or a completely custom construction, we are ready to
      discuss your requirements.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 pb-20 mx-auto max-w-4xl text-center">
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 p-8">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Start your fabric design consultation</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-muted">Tell us about your performance targets and we will propose an engineering path.</p>
      <a
        href="/contact"
        class="mt-4 inline-block px-6 py-3 bg-primary text-white font-semibold rounded-md hover:bg-primary/90"
        >Contact our engineering team</a
      >
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
